[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026646&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026646&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I went over this in a previous message.  In order to nip further rumors
in the bud, I will repeat the gist:

The purpose of nicknames is to keep things working while the official
name of a host is changed.

The NIC's view is that a "reasonable number" of nicknames for any host
is normally ZERO.  However, names do change.  When a host's name is
changed, its old name must be retained for some time (not forever) as
a nickname.  Thus, ONE nickname is normally allowed, as it is unusual
for hosts to change names more than once within a short time.  Our
software can certainly handle large numbers of nicknames, and we can
certainly accomodate hosts which are forced to change their official
name again before the new one has "set" firmly.  But nicknames just
for the purpose of nicknames, or frivolous name changes, have to be
strongly discouraged.  Remember that only the official name is ever to
be used in outgoing mail headers; it makes sense to extend this to
anything outgoing.

This is a general principle.  The new domain template file only
applies it to the DNS server hosts for a particular domain; it is not
saying anything about the name of the domain, or the names of hosts
within the domain (although I think most domain administrators will
sooner or later adopt a similar principle).  Apparently the file should
be clearer on this point.
